abstract: Not the fight over abortion. Not the fight over impeachment. Maybe Biden? Nah.
snippet: Not the fight over abortion. Not the fight over impeachment. Maybe Biden? Nah.
lead_paragraph: Bret Stephens: Hi there, Gail. Until last week or so, I think there was a fairly broad consensus (including between the two of us) that impeachment was not a great idea. But now a Republican congressman, Michigan’s Justin Amash, has declared that Donald Trump has “engaged in impeachable conduct,” and the debate has resumed in earnest. Are you rethinking your earlier misgivings about impeachment?

abstract: While some of the 2020 Democrats have sworn off big donors, Joe Biden and his campaign have welcomed them into the fold.
snippet: While some of the 2020 Democrats have sworn off big donors, Joe Biden and his campaign have welcomed them into the fold.
lead_paragraph: A couple of days before Joseph R. Biden Jr. announced his campaign for president, he spent 45 minutes on the phone with John Morgan, a major Florida political donor. As they chatted, Mr. Morgan suggested that the former vice president would be jealous to know that he was lounging poolside, a cigar in hand, with his two German shepherds by his side.

abstract: Another Democratic town hall event on the channel liberals love to hate drew sizable ratings — and underscored the split between its news and opinion sides.
snippet: Another Democratic town hall event on the channel liberals love to hate drew sizable ratings — and underscored the split between its news and opinion sides.
lead_paragraph: The night began with a campaign-style biographical video and ended with a standing ovation. The candidate called President Trump’s behavior “grotesque” and lamented the “media noise machine on the right wing.” He attacked Tucker Carlson and Laura Ingraham by name.

abstract: In the On Politics newsletter: The president and some allies are distancing themselves from the Alabama abortion ban, worried that the law goes beyond what voters support.

abstract: In the 44th season finale, Rudd played Pete Buttigieg and DJ Khaled offered a tribute to Nipsey Hussle.
snippet: In the 44th season finale, Rudd played Pete Buttigieg and DJ Khaled offered a tribute to Nipsey Hussle.
lead_paragraph: A “Saturday Night Live” season finale is traditionally an occasion for the show to pull out all the stops, leave everything on the stage, tear it all down and figure out how to put it back together in the fall. In this weekend’s conclusion to “S.N.L.” Season 44 (which was hosted by Paul Rudd), the musical guest DJ Khaled certainly brought it, performing with a pantheon of surprise performers including Lil Wayne, Big Sean, Meek Mill, SZA and John Legend, while also paying tribute to the rapper Nipsey Hussle, who was fatally shot in March.

abstract: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From rising tensions with Iran to the still-growing Democratic presidential field, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: The newest debate among the Democratic presidential candidates is whether accepting an invitation from Fox News is a Faustian bargain.
snippet: The newest debate among the Democratic presidential candidates is whether accepting an invitation from Fox News is a Faustian bargain.
lead_paragraph: Hi. Welcome to On Politics, your guide to the day in national politics. I’m Lisa Lerer, your host.
